28. Juni 2022

Background & Focus

Why designing science communication?

  • Teachers are encouraged to consider evidence in their professional practice (slavin.2020?)

  • teachers rarely draw on research evidence in their daily practice (e.g., Thomm et al., 2021)

  • different strategies exist to increase / foster teachers’ engagement with evidence (Shavelson, 2020)

  • current approaches: toward a more intuitive science communication
    (Farley-Ripple et al., 2020; Hedges, 2018)

Background & Focus

Why looking at effect sizes?

  • There exist several “clearing house” approaches
    “best available […] evidence from systematic research” (Sackett et al., 1996, p. 71)

  • particularly evaluated according to the extent to which it allows to assess treatment effectiveness, i.e. the investigation of whether a treatment works (APA, 2002)

  • Meta-analyses (research syntheses) = highest level of evidence
    ES = key information to be communicated (Burns et al., 2011)

Background & Focus

Why looking at visualizations?

  • scientists & clearing houses typically use standardized textual representations (Cohen, 1988)

  • textual representations of effect sizes are challenging for teachers’ perception and understanding (Hanel & Mehler, 2019; Lortie-Forgues et al., 2021)

  • Alternative: visualizations (Franconeri et al., 2021)

Background & Focus

What we know about visualizing data (in general)

Background & Focus

What we know about visualizing data (for lay people)

accurate estimation of statistical information needed for the evaluation of effect sizes: Type of visualization plays a role

  • box plots: spread; distribution
  • bar/line plot: mean
  • modified stock chart: maxima, minima; spread

(Albers et al., 2014; Pierce & Chick, 2013)

Objectives & Reserach Questions

Exploratory & descriptive: Visualization types

  1. Does visualization type affect A, B, C in assessing effect sizes?
  2. Which visualization types produce the highest ratings in A, B, C?

Objectives & Reserach Questions

Exploratory & descriptive: Enrichment options

  1. Does visualization type affect A, B, C in assessing effect sizes?
  2. Which visualization types produce the highest ratings in A, B, C?
  3. How do visualizations with visual benchmarks affect A, B, C, compared to visualizations without benchmarks?
  4. How do visualizations with textual cues affect A, B, C compared to visualizations without textual cues and a control group?

Study 1

Visualization types: Design

  • student teachers (N = Bayesian updating)
  • 4 x 6 within-design
    • 4 visualization types
    • 6 effect sizes
  • randomizations
    • order of conditions
    • vignettes (1 of 4 randomized between)

Study 1

Visualization types: Measures

  • Perceived task difficulty (Marcus et al., 1996)

  • Sensitivity (Merk et al., under review)
  • Accuracy
  • Efficiency

  • Perceived informativeness (Lortie-Forgues et al., 2021;
    Hanel & Mehler, 2019)
  • Perceived value
  • Intention to use

Study 2

Statistical Analyses

  • approximate adjusted fractional Bayes factors (Hoijtink et al., 2019)

Benchmarking

H3.1: \(\mu(sens)_{noBench} < \mu(sens)_{Bench}\)

H3.2: \(\mu(acc)_{noBench} < \mu(acc)_{Bench}\)

H3.3: \(\mu(inf)_{noBench} < \mu(inf)_{Bench}\)

H3.4: \(\mu(diff)_{noBench} > \mu(diff)_{Bench}\)

Study 2

Statistical Analyses

  • approximate adjusted fractional Bayes factors (Hoijtink et al., 2019)

Textual Cues

H4.1: \((\mu(sens)_{VisOnly} , \mu(sens)_{TextOnly}) < \mu(sens)_{Vis+Text}\)

H4.2: \((\mu(acc)_{VisOnly} , \mu(acc)_{TextOnly}) < \mu(acc)_{Vis+Text}\)

H4.3: \((\mu(inf)_{VisOnly} , \mu(inf)_{TextOnly}) < \mu(inf)_{Vis+Text}\)

H4.4: \((\mu(diff)_{VisOnly} , \mu(diff)_{TextOnly}) > \mu(diff)_{Vis+Text}\)
